  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-bark-500">
    Part of the <a href="/clusters/soil-and-amendments/" class="text-moss-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-moss-900">Soil & Amendments cluster</a>.
  </p>

  <!-- Mobile TOC accordion — below the calculator, collapsed by default, hidden on desktop -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="accordion" />

  <LeadMagnetForm
    client:load
    listId={leadMagnet.listId}
    clusterName={leadMagnet.clusterName}
    icon={leadMagnet.icon}
    description={`A one-page PDF of the ${cluster.name.toLowerCase()} math from this site, emailed once.`}
  />

  <article class="prose prose-bark mt-8 max-w-none prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-bark-900 prose-h2:mt-12 prose-h2:scroll-mt-24 prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:font-semibold prose-h3:text-lg prose-h3:font-semibold prose-a:text-moss-700 prose-strong:text-bark-900">

    <h2 id="how-much-compost-do-i-need">How Much Compost Do I Need?</h2>
    <p>
      How much compost you need depends on what you&rsquo;re doing with it. <strong>Top-dressing</strong> an existing bed or lawn &mdash; spreading a thin layer over the surface to feed the soil without digging it in &mdash; typically calls for <strong>1 to 3 inches</strong> of compost. <strong>Mixing compost into new bed soil</strong>, by contrast, means blending it through the whole root zone at a much higher proportion: the standard raised bed mix used throughout this site&rsquo;s soil calculators is <strong>60% topsoil, 30% compost, and 10% perlite or coarse sand</strong> for drainage.
    </p>
    <figure class="my-6 float-right ml-6 w-48 sm:w-64">
      <img
        src="/compost-calculator-bin-and-bed.svg"
        alt="A compost bin next to a raised garden bed receiving a layer of finished compost"
        width="400"
        height="250"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-xl border border-moss-100 bg-moss-50/30"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-bark-500">
        Top-dressing and mixing in call for very different amounts of compost.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Once you know your target depth, the volume math is straightforward: multiply your area by the depth (converted to feet) to get cubic feet, then convert to cubic yards or bags depending on how you&rsquo;re buying it. The calculator above does this for any area and depth, and also estimates the weight of what you&rsquo;re hauling &mdash; useful if you&rsquo;re the one carrying the bags or filling the wheelbarrow.
    </p>
    <p>
      One practical note: compost settles after it&rsquo;s spread, especially if it&rsquo;s not fully finished or if it&rsquo;s watered in heavily. Buying the exact calculated amount with zero margin can leave you slightly short a few weeks later &mdash; see Common Mistakes below.
    </p>

    <h2 id="compost-application-rates-by-use">Compost Application Rates by Use</h2>
    <p>
      Application depth and coverage vary significantly by use case. The table below shows typical reference rates; always use the calculator above to convert these to your exact area.
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-left text-sm not-prose">
        <caption class="mb-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-bark-400">
          Compost Application Rates by Use Case
        </caption>
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b-2 border-moss-200 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-bark-500">
            <th scope="col" class="py-2.5 pr-4 font-semibold">Use Case</th>
            <th scope="col" class="py-2.5 pr-4 font-semibold">Depth / Rate</th>
            <th scope="col" class="py-2.5 font-semibold">Coverage (1 cu yd)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-bark-700">
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Incorporating into new bed soil</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">3&ndash;4 in (tilled in)</td>
            <td class="py-2">~100&ndash;150 sq ft per cu yd<br /><span class="text-bark-500 text-xs">(~1 cu yd per 500 sq ft at 2&ndash;3 in)</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50 bg-moss-50/30">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Top-dressing existing garden beds</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">1&ndash;3 in</td>
            <td class="py-2">~100&ndash;300 sq ft per cu yd</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Topdressing over grass seed / lawn</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">&frac14;&ndash;&frac12; in</td>
            <td class="py-2">~650&ndash;1,300 sq ft per cu yd<br /><span class="text-bark-500 text-xs">(~1 cu yd per 2,000 sq ft at &frac14; in)</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50 bg-moss-50/30">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Raised bed mix (compost component)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">~30% of total volume</td>
            <td class="py-2">Depends on bed depth &mdash; use the Raised Bed Soil Calculator</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Container potting mix (amendment)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">20&ndash;30% by volume</td>
            <td class="py-2">Blended into potting mix at fill time</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 id="finished-vs-unfinished-compost">Finished vs. Unfinished Compost</h2>
    <p>
      Not all compost is ready to use the moment it comes out of the bin or bag. <strong>Finished (mature) compost</strong> is dark, crumbly, and smells earthy &mdash; like forest floor, not ammonia or rotting food. It has fully broken down and is biologically stable: it can be applied at any time, even directly around established plants, without risk of harming roots or stealing nitrogen from the soil.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Unfinished compost</strong> is still actively decomposing. The microbes doing that decomposition consume soil nitrogen as fuel, which can <em>temporarily reduce</em> the nitrogen available to your plants &mdash; a process called nitrogen immobilization or nitrogen tie-up. Unfinished compost can also release compounds (organic acids, heat from microbial activity) that stress tender roots if applied right at planting time. The practical rule: apply unfinished compost <strong>at least 2&ndash;4 weeks before planting</strong> and work it into the soil so decomposition can continue in place and nitrogen levels can restabilize before seeds or transplants go in. For top-dressing around established plants, finished compost is strongly preferred &mdash; unfinished material sitting on the surface breaks down slowly in open air and can mat, impeding water infiltration.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you&rsquo;re buying bagged compost from a garden center, most products are finished &mdash; check that the label says &ldquo;fully composted&rdquo; or &ldquo;mature compost.&rdquo; Compost from a home pile is finished when it no longer heats up when turned, has a uniform dark color and earthy smell, and you can&rsquo;t identify any of the original input materials.
    </p>

    <h2 id="what-can-and-cant-go-in-compost">What Can (and Can&rsquo;t) Go in Compost</h2>
    <p>
      A working compost pile needs a rough balance of <strong>&ldquo;greens&rdquo;</strong> (nitrogen-rich material like vegetable scraps, coffee grounds, and fresh grass clippings) and <strong>&ldquo;browns&rdquo;</strong> (carbon-rich material like dry leaves, cardboard, and straw). A commonly cited starting ratio is roughly <strong>2 to 3 parts browns for every 1 part greens by volume</strong> &mdash; too many greens and the pile turns slimy and smells like ammonia; too many browns and it barely breaks down at all. You don&rsquo;t need to measure precisely, just keep adding browns whenever you add a load of kitchen scraps.
    </p>
    <p>
      A few things are generally kept out of a home compost pile. <strong>Meat, eggs, and dairy</strong> attract rodents and other pests, produce strong odors as they decompose, and carry a higher risk of pathogens that a backyard pile&rsquo;s heat usually isn&rsquo;t sustained or high enough to fully neutralize &mdash; industrial composting facilities can process these safely because they maintain much higher, more consistent temperatures than a home bin. <strong>Ash</strong> is a subtler problem: even a modest amount pushes the pile&rsquo;s pH sharply alkaline, which can slow down the microbes doing the actual decomposing, and charcoal or coal ash specifically can carry residues that are harmful to plants. A light dusting of plain wood ash is sometimes tolerated, but it&rsquo;s easy to overdo, so most guides simply recommend leaving ash out of the pile entirely and using it elsewhere in the garden if at all.
    </p>
    <p>
      Diseased plant material and anything treated with pesticide or herbicide are also worth keeping out &mdash; a home pile usually won&rsquo;t get hot enough to reliably kill plant pathogens or break down chemical residues, and either one can end up right back in your garden bed.
    </p>

    <h2 id="worked-example">Worked Example</h2>
    <p>
      Say you&rsquo;re top-dressing a <strong>4 &times; 8 ft raised bed</strong> with a <strong>2-inch layer</strong> of compost.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Area:</strong> 4 ft &times; 8 ft = <strong>32 sq ft</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Cubic feet:</strong> 32 &times; (2 &divide; 12) = <strong>~5.3 cu ft</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Cubic yards:</strong> 5.3 &divide; 27 = <strong>~0.2 cu yd</strong> (most suppliers round this up to a 1/4 yard minimum delivery).</li>
      <li><strong>Bags:</strong> at 1.5 cu ft per bag, 5.3 &divide; 1.5 = <strong>4 bags</strong> (rounded up).</li>
      <li><strong>Estimated weight:</strong> 5.3 cu ft &times; 44-50 lb/cu ft = <strong>~235-267 lb</strong> (about 107-121 kg).</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      So a 4&times;8 bed at a 2-inch top-dressing needs roughly <strong>4 bags of compost</strong>, weighing somewhere around <strong>a quarter ton</strong> total &mdash; worth knowing before you decide whether to haul it in bags or have it delivered loose by the yard. The calculator above runs this same math instantly for any bed size, depth, or bag size.
    </p>

    <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Applying unfinished compost right at planting time.</strong> As explained in the <a href="#finished-vs-unfinished-compost">Finished vs. Unfinished</a> section above, compost that&rsquo;s still actively decomposing temporarily ties up soil nitrogen and can stress tender roots. Finished compost is safe to apply anytime; unfinished compost needs at least 2&ndash;4 weeks worked into the soil before planting. If it still looks like recognizable food scraps or smells sour or ammonia-like, it&rsquo;s not ready.</li>
      <li><strong>Wrong greens-to-browns ratio.</strong> A pile that&rsquo;s too heavy on greens turns anaerobic and smells bad; too heavy on browns and it stalls out. If your pile smells off or isn&rsquo;t breaking down, adjust the ratio before adding anything else.</li>
      <li><strong>Not accounting for settling.</strong> Fresh compost settles as it beds in and water works through it, so a layer that looked like 2 inches on delivery day can settle to noticeably less within a few weeks. Buying 10-15% extra covers this without much added cost.</li>
      <li><strong>Over-applying.</strong> More compost isn&rsquo;t automatically better &mdash; piling on several inches every season can throw off soil nutrient balance and, in containers, crowd out the mineral component the roots also need. Stick to the recommended depth for the job you&rsquo;re actually doing.</li>
    </ul>

    <FAQBlock id="compost-calculator-faq" heading="Compost Calculator FAQ" faqs={faqs} />

    <h2 id="sources-and-further-reading">Sources &amp; further reading</h2>
    <p>
      Volume and bag-count formulas here draw on Texas A&amp;M AgriLife Extension&rsquo;s <a href="https://travis-tx.tamu.edu/about-2/horticulture/soils-and-composting-for-austin/how-much-compost-soil-or-mulch/" rel="noopener">&ldquo;How Much Compost, Soil or Mulch?&rdquo;</a> guide. For more on how we build and verify the formulas behind every calculator on this site, see our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>. For how compost fits alongside topsoil, garden soil, and mulch in a full project, see our <a href="/clusters/soil-and-amendments/">complete guide to soil and amendments</a>.
    </p>

    <RelatedCalculatorsList id="related-calculators" items={[
      { name: 'Soil & Amendments cluster', url: '/clusters/soil-and-amendments/', anchorText: 'Soil & Amendments cluster', note: 'more soil, mulch, and amendment calculators in this cluster.' },
      { name: 'Raised Bed Soil Calculator', url: '/calculators/raised-bed-soil-calculator/', note: 'figure out how much compost to mix into your raised bed soil.' },
      { name: 'Mulch Calculator', url: '/calculators/mulch-calculator/', note: 'compare with our Mulch Calculator for top-dressing with bark or wood mulch instead.' },
    ]} />

    <p class="mt-12 text-sm text-bark-500">
      Last updated: {formattedDate}.
    </p>
  </article>
</CalculatorLayout>
